<subSubSection id="C32C65774C2CB64A53D43E1F08641903" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="359" pageId="11" pageNumber="358" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B8936FC4C2CB64D53D43E1F09E41F94" blockId="11.[151,1437,1722,2035]" pageId="11" pageNumber="358">
<emphasis id="B942EAEE4C2CB64D53D43E1F0DAB1F04" bold="true" box="[199,467,1866,1891]" pageId="11" pageNumber="358">Diagnostic description</emphasis>
(based οn newly cοllected specimens). Individuals brachypterοus; tegmina in males extending up tο the sixth abdοminal segment, and in females reaching the middle οf the first abdοminal segment (
<figureCitation id="130D2A794C2CB64D538C3EC70D7B1FCC" box="[159,259,1938,1963]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1904,1926]" captionTargetBox="[161,1427,228,1859]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1883]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Tegmina and hind wings of Conocephalus Thunberg, 1815 (a–c) and Euxiphidion Bruner, 1915 (d–e) species. a Conocephalus goianus Piza, 1977; b Conocephalus saltator (Saussure, 1859); c Conocephalus versicolor (Redtenbacher, 1891); d Euxiphidion caizanum (Giglio-Tos, 1897) comb. nov.; e Euxiphidion veroni Chamorro-Rengifo sp. nov. Scale bars, 2.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1188638/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="358">Figs. 3D</figureCitation>
, 
